caption.text:
it ends with us: film & book review üå∏

*may contain spoilers of the book*

the book üìñ
this is the first book in a LONG while that i was quite shocked at and that i could NOT put down. the plot twist took me by such surprise that i had my jaw hanging open. my reread allowed me to pick up on so many red flags that i missed the first time round - which is quite funny really, because lily missed them too. i sobbed at the authors note and gave it a 5 star rating despite the ellen letters.

there are so many themes played with that could be triggering. this book was criticised heavily in the media for romanticising DV/SA, and i dont think that it does at all. i think it shows you how easily you can slip into a trap and that not all men look like they would hurt you‚Ä¶ some are charming and kind at first. It shows that anyone could be Lily. 

the film üé¨
what can i say.. i really enjoyed it. as soon as the opening credits rolled, i felt really at home as i‚Äôve known these characters for so long. I thought the story was brought to life remarkably well. characters that i wasnt that fond of in the book (alyssa and lily‚Äôs mum) were actually some of my favourites in the film. i thought justin baldoni played the perfect ryle. i think the age markup was necessary.

my criticisms would be that the scenes between young atlas and lily were not built enough, for some people who hadn‚Äôt read the book, they may have been a bit confused as to why they were such big parts of each others lives?! also some big lines weren‚Äôt delivered with enough OOMPH for me‚Ä¶ i really wanted more from the ‚Äúfall in love with me‚Äù line.. iykyk ü§£

I would highly recommend this, I think overall they did a great job at bringing it to the big screen but PLEASE read the book first! 

If you‚Äôve watched this, how did it compare to the book?

caption.text:
Three Hole Thursday this week sees this Delta Tristar-500 (N764DA) seconds from touchdown at EIDW (DUB) on 25 July 2000. She was originally delivered to Air Canada as (C-GAGF) on 26 February 1981 and would stay with them until being sold to DL as above registration in August of 1991. She would be retired in January 2001 and made her final flight to KVCV and was parked up. She would eventually be sold off to ARC Aerospace Industries in December of 2012 and be stripped of anything of value and towed to death row. She would be sold off for the final time to Jet Midwest and her registration cancelled in March of 2013. She died the next month in April 2013. Note the Air France Concorde in the background. Pic from the Carl Ford collection.
